meanings":["English (mainly Lancashire and Cumbria):","habitational name from Pennington in Furness (Lancashire), which derives from Old English <i>pening</i> ‘penny’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’, or from Pennington in Leigh (Lancashire), which probably derives from the Old English personal name <i>Pinna</i> + the Old English groupname suffix <i>-ingas</i> (genitive <i>-inga-</i>) + Old English <i>tūn</i>.","habitational name from Pennington (Hampshire), or from Penton Grafton or Penton Mewsey (both Hampshire); see   Penton  . All have the same etymology as Pennington in Furness; see 1 above."],"variants":[{"name":"Penington","meanings":["English (Lancashire): variant of   Pennington  . This form of the surname is rare in Britain and Ireland.","History: Edward Penington, born in 1667 in Amersham, Buckinghamshire, England, was appointed surveyor-general of the province of PA in 1698 and accompanied William Penn to Philadelphia."]},{"name":"Penton","meanings":["English (mainly Hampshire):","habitational name from Penton Grafton or Penton Mewsey (both Hanmpshire), or from a shortened form of   Pennington   2. The placenames denoted a farm or estate for which a penny tax was payable (Old English <i>pening</i> ‘penny’ + <i>tūn</i>).","in north-west England, a shortened form of   Pennington   1, from either of the places called Pennington in Lancashire."]}]},{"name":"Benedict","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Church Latin <i>benedictus</i> ‘blessed’. This was the name of the saint (  <i>c.</i>480– <i>c.</i>550 ) who composed the Benedictine rule of Christian monastic life that is still followed in essence by all Western orders. He was born near Spoleto in Umbria, central Italy. After studying in Rome, he went to live as a hermit at Subiaco, and later organized groups of followers and imitators into monastic cells. In  <i>c.</i>529  he moved to Monte Cassino, where he founded the great monastery that is still the centre of the Benedictine order. His rule is simple, restrained, and practical.  See also  Bennett ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Sir Benedict Pennington was born in 1130, in Muncaster, Cumberland, England as the son of Sir Gamel Pennington and Ulfsdotter. He had at least 2 sons with Agnes Lindsay. He died in 1185, in his hometown, at the age of 55."},"et":{"1130–1185":"1130–1185","1133–Female":"1133–Surnud","1135–Male":"1135–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1160–1208":"1160–1208","–1165":"–1165","1090–1170":"1090–1170","1090":"1090","1127":"1127","about 1160":"umbes 1160","1135":"1135","1133":"1133","1165":"1165","1130":"1130","1185":"1185","1160":"1160","1170":"1170","1208":"1208","Mulcastre, Farnley, Yorkshire, England":"Farnley, Yorkshire, England","Muncaster, Cumberland, England":"Muncaster, Cumberland, England","Muncaster, Cumbria, England":"Muncaster, Cumberland, England"},"fi":{"1130–1185":"1130–1185","1133–Female":"1133–Kuollut","1135–Male":"1135–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1160–1208":"1160–1208","–1165":"–1165","1090–1170":"1090–1170","1090":"1090","1127":"1127","about 1160":"noin 1160","1135":"1135","1133":"1133","1165":"1165","1130":"1130","1185":"1185","1160":"1160","1170":"1170","1208":"1208","Mulcastre, Farnley, Yorkshire, England":"Farnley, Yorkshire, England","Muncaster, Cumberland, England":"Muncaster, Cumberland, England","Muncaster, Cumbria, England":"Muncaster, Cumberland, England"},"fr":{"1130–1185":"1130–1185","1133–Female":"1133–Décédée","1135–Male":"1135–Décédé","–Female":"Décédée","1160–1208":"1160–1208","–1165":"–1165","1090–1170":"1090–1170","1090":"1090","1127":"1127","about 1160":"environ 1160","1135":"1135","1133":"1133","1165":"1165","1130":"1130","1185":"1185","1160":"1160","1170":"1170","1208":"1208","Mulcastre, Farnley, Yorkshire, England":"Farnley, Everwyck, Angleterre","Muncaster, Cumberland, England":"Muncaster, Cumberland, Angleterre","Muncaster, Cumbria, England":"Muncaster, Cumberland, A